  "text": "## Kubernetes Scheduler Plugin Framework Architecture\n\n### Framework Interface Definitions\nThe core framework interfaces are defined in **pkg/scheduler/framework/interface.go**. The parent interface **Plugin** is the base for all scheduling framework plugins. Key plugin interfaces include:\n\n- **PreEnqueuePlugin**: Called before adding pods to activeQ\n- **QueueSortPlugin**: Used to sort pods in the scheduling queue\n- **PreFilterPlugin**: Called at the beginning of the scheduling cycle; can pre-compute and optionally filter candidate nodes\n- **FilterPlugin**: Filters out nodes that cannot run a pod\n- **PostFilterPlugin**: Called when a pod cannot be scheduled (enables preemption logic)\n- **PreScorePlugin**: Informational extension point after filtering passes\n- **ScorePlugin**: Scores nodes based on criteria; implements **ScoreExtensions** for normalization\n- **ReservePlugin**: Reserves resources for a pod\n- **PermitPlugin**: Permits or denies pod binding\n- **PreBindPlugin**: Pre-bind logic before binding\n- **BindPlugin**: Binds the pod to a node\n- **PostBindPlugin**: Post-bind logic\n\nThe **Status** struct and **WaitingPod** interface are also defined here to represent plugin execution results and permit-phase state.\n\n### ScheduleOne Orchestration Function\nThe function **func (sched *Scheduler) ScheduleOne(ctx context.Context)** in **pkg/scheduler/schedule_one.go** is the main orchestration function that drives the scheduling cycle for a single pod. It:\n\n1. Retrieves the next pod from the scheduling queue\n2. Selects the appropriate framework (scheduler profile) for the pod\n3. Calls **schedulingCycle()** to attempt scheduling the pod\n4. On success, asynchronously calls **bindingCycle()** to bind the pod\n\nThe **schedulingCycle()** function calls the actual scheduler's **SchedulePod()** method, which invokes the framework plugins through multiple extension points.\n\nThe **bindingCycle()** function handles the actual binding and post-bind operations.\n\n### Top-Level Scheduler Struct and Run Method\nThe **Scheduler** struct in **pkg/scheduler/scheduler.go** is the top-level component with the following key fields:\n\n- **Cache**: Internal cache of node and pod state\n- **NextPod**: Function to retrieve the next pod to schedule from the queue\n- **FailureHandler**: Called upon scheduling failure\n- **SchedulePod**: Function that invokes the scheduling algorithm through framework plugins\n- **SchedulingQueue**: Holds pods to be scheduled\n- **Profiles**: Map of scheduler profiles (each with its own framework)\n\nThe **func (sched *Scheduler) Run(ctx context.Context)** method in **pkg/scheduler/scheduler.go** is the entry point that:\n\n1. Starts the SchedulingQueue\n2. Launches a goroutine running **ScheduleOne** in a loop via **wait.UntilWithContext()**\n3. Blocks until context is done, then closes the queue and plugins\n\n### frameworkImpl Runtime\nThe **frameworkImpl** struct in **pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/framework.go** is the component responsible for initializing and running scheduler plugins. It contains:\n\n- Lists of plugin implementations for each extension point (preEnqueuePlugins, filterPlugins, scorePlugins, etc.)\n- A plugin registry and metrics recording\n- Methods to run plugins at each extension point\n\nKey plugin invocation methods:\n\n- **RunPreFilterPlugins()**: Runs pre-filter plugins\n- **RunFilterPlugins()**: Runs filter plugins on a node; returns first failure\n- **RunPostFilterPlugins()**: Runs post-filter plugins for preemption logic\n- **RunPreScorePlugins()**: Runs pre-score plugins\n- **RunScorePlugins()**: Runs scoring plugins in parallel on all nodes, normalizes scores, and applies weights\n- **RunReservePluginsReserve()**: Reserves resources\n- **RunPreBindPlugins()**: Pre-bind plugins\n- **RunBindPlugins()**: Bind plugins to attach pod to node\n- **RunPostBindPlugins()**: Post-bind plugins\n- **RunPermitPlugins()**: Permit plugins for final approval\n\nThese methods implement the complete plugin execution orchestration, including parallelization, metrics recording, and error handling.\n\n### Plugin Registry and NewInTreeRegistry\nThe **Registry** type in **pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/registry.go** is a map from plugin name to **PluginFactory** function. It provides methods to register, unregister, and merge plugins.\n\n**PluginFactory** is a function signature for building a plugin:\n```go\ntype PluginFactory = func(ctx context.Context, configuration runtime.Object, f framework.Handle) (framework.Plugin, error)\n```\n\n**PluginFactoryWithFts** allows injecting feature gates:\n```go\ntype PluginFactoryWithFts func(context.Context, runtime.Object, framework.Handle, plfeature.Features) (framework.Plugin, error)\n```\n\nThe **func NewInTreeRegistry() runtime.Registry** function in **pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/registry.go** builds the registry with all in-tree plugins:\n\n- dynamicresources\n- imagelocality\n- tainttoleration\n- nodename\n- nodeports\n- nodeaffinity\n- podtopologyspread\n- nodeunschedulable\n- noderesources (Fit and BalancedAllocation)\n- volumebinding\n- volumerestrictions\n- volumezone\n- nodevolumelimits (CSI)\n- interpodaffinity\n- queuesort (PrioritySort)\n- defaultbinder\n- defaultpreemption\n- schedulinggates\n\nOut-of-tree plugins can be registered via the **WithFrameworkOutOfTreeRegistry** option passed to the scheduler.\n\n### Summary\nThe scheduler framework provides a plugin-based architecture where:\n1. **Scheduler.Run()** starts the scheduling loop\n2. **ScheduleOne()** coordinates the scheduling of individual pods\n3. **schedulingCycle()** invokes the framework plugins through multiple extension points\n4. **frameworkImpl** executes each plugin interface at designated extension points\n5. **Registry** maintains all available plugins (in-tree and out-of-tree)\n6. Each plugin interface enables different aspects of the scheduling decision (filtering, scoring, binding, etc.)\n"
}

